Community Day is this Saturday, Nov 10 from 1 to 4!  We will have Community Day at the museum.  Here is what you need to know!

Donations:  The focus for giving back this CD is the Auburn City Toy Drive
(https://www.auburnalabama.org/toy-drive/ ).  If you are able, we invite you to bring an unwrapped gift, age appropriate for 2 - 8 year olds.  This can really make a difference for some families during the holiday season. We are still planning on having a raffle, however, since no monetary donations are allowed in the toy drive, ALL money generated from the raffle will go towards purchasing more toys.  

Tim Hardwick is taking the lead in the raffle and has more information about the Toy Drive if you have any questions

Please go to the website and indicate if you are coming or not.  Also, If you are able, please sign up to bring to bring a food item. (COOKIES!!). 

www.auburnpokemongo.com

Next Sunday the 21st is Beldum Community Day!  No football to interfere this time. Community day will be at the musuem again. This is an amazing chance to grow as a community, get to know one another, and give back! 

Donations: Based on feedback from the website, this month we are focusing on the Alzheimer’s Association.  There will be several ways to donate. A website, $1 Alzheimer’s Ribbons, team stickers, and a raffle. 100% of the donations will go to Alzheimer’s Association.  What a huge impact it would be if everyone donated just $1!  Blaine will be taking the lead in the donations. More info about raffle and donations will be on auburnpokemongo.com 

Food:  On the menu so far:  smoked butt and chicken. Please go to the website and sign up to bring sides and more!  Let’s continue to have a successful and amazing community day. Did I mention “Lee’s cookies?”

We are looking forward to seeing everyone around noon on the 21st for Community Day!

messages.text:
Here it is: Hey everyone!  It seems like coordinating raids has been a bit hectic lately. I know it can be confusing when there are lots of people doing multiple raids. One thing that’s really helpful is to go ahead and state a time that you’d like to do the raid. Then people can figure out whether they can make it or not. 

One of the things that has made this Pogo community great is how everyone helps each other out. So, if you set a raid time, don’t start the raid before that time. Make sure everyone is there first; it really won’t kill you to wait a minute or two for someone who has said they are coming. That being said, don’t tell people you’ll be there in 5 if it’s really going to be 15. Just try to make the next one.

messages.name: Does more updates than Niantic
messages.text: Processing can be intense and I can queue the tasks. Amazon s3 is great for housing static stuff it’s cheap. I don’t know how much you know about requests, but when you go to a website, you request that page, and then make a request for each style sheet, JavaScript page, and each and every image and video. So I limit the requests to my server that does the web work to only web page info, and let amazon handle the static stuff.

messages.name: Does more updates than Niantic
messages.text: I am rare in that I do both front end development, back end development, and the design.

messages.name: Does more updates than Niantic
messages.text: I have about 1200 websites @Win a raid for 10 bananas

messages.name: Does more updates than Niantic
messages.text: I have servers set up to handle media, so the pokestop images, gym images, the gallery images and videos, I process on that server. Create the different sizes, encode videos for all browsers and such. Then they are moved to an Amazon server. I have servers that process messaging. Email, phone text, Facebook, Twitter, and GroupMe happen there. I have the webserver that handles the website and database. It’s a lot to build at once. I built several sites like http://www.aotourism.com and http://www.campflorida.com that use this system setup. I have been building sites for 18 years.
